\begin_layout Title
Diary – Part Ten–H
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
June 2026 – present
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepštas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Unlike parts one through nine in this series,
 this one is not really about the language–learning effort.
 It is instead a private diary;
 a continuation of Part Ten–G,
 which got over–long.
 It is not curated for human consumption;
 I am making the assumption that no human being will ever actually read this.
 Thus,
 it is filled with random stuff I feel like writing.
 Some of it is very personal,
 some of it is nonsense.
 Mostly,
 I am finding that the act of writing helps otherwise vague and scattered thoughts quantum–collapse into a more coherent form,
 where I can examine them,
 like a dead butterfly pinned down in a display case.
 Dead words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
If you are interested in this content,
 then you should ask an AI agent to read it,
 then ask the AI agent to pretended that it's me,
 then talk to virtual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

me
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 I believe that present–day LLM technology is sufficiently advanced to be able to do this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part Ten already got an introduction.
 A different way of thinking is about what is going on here is that this is a form of life–logging.
 Or,
 in 18th century terms,
 a diary.
 Just not anywhere near as compelling as those written by the famous diarists.
 This one is more of a mental self–portrait.
 And not even for you but for myself.
 Not to cast a narcissistic gaze at my own words,
 but to organize my own thoughts.
 Still in the experimental stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
5 June 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I was tortured by my dreams last night.
 Rather than repress them,
 where they can do continued psychic harm,
 I will try to relive them now.
 Where they may cause either more harm,
 or possibly bring around catharsis.
 Its a gamble,
 although I honestly expect neither outcome,
 but a third:
 a fading away into pointlessness.
 I felt a shadow of depression as I wrote the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pointlessness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Pointless things (objects,
 activities) seem stupid,
 but pointless emotional journeys seem sad.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The soul,
 as primarily incarnated in humans,
 is built on a foundation of light.
 I use the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because none of the others fit:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hope
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (hope implies expectation of a better future;
 but we are already here,
 so there is no comparative of better or worse.) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

joy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (joy is wonderous,
 and a strong emotion:
 bliss,
 ecstasy.
 Our base foundation is not ecstatic,
 its merely normal,
 existential.
 But I don't like the words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

existential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because it has negative overtones,
 or at least dismissive of a positive foundation for existence.) I can't think of any other words right now,
 because its morning,
 and I have not wiped the sleep from my eyes.
 The intent is to say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This wanders on some tricky territory.
 Psychologists have a map of the base settings for humans,
 going under trms like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

temperment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

disposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 a base somatic level or setting.
 Some people are just angry;
 others just sad.
 I guess an overall joyous disposition is rather uncommon.
 Let me ask google:...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well,
 that was a useless exercise;
 here's a synopsis:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
About 1.5% to 6% of the population possess a chronic,
 low–level baseline of sadness (that persists regardless of external circumstances.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
DSM 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Persistent Depressive Disorder
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Dysthymia)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Approx 15% of the population is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

neurotic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 scoring high on that axis of the Big Five personality test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The CDC reports a general dissatisfaction baseline of 5%,
 i.e.
 general dissatisfaction independent of specific life events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Approx 50% of your baseline happiness is determined by genetics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Early life temperment:
 such individuals report anxiety and lack of self–confidence even in childhood,
 suggesting early–onset emotional setting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then I asked about a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sunny disposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sunny disposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is more common,
 at 14% to 30% of the global population being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very happy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exceptionally optimistic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Extremely Happy – 15% – daily joy and satisfaction despite minor stressors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Dispositional optimists – 20% – expect favorable outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Very Satisfied Genetic Profile – Of those with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 version of the 5-HTT promotor gene,
 35% report being very happy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sunny disposition is typically a combination of high extraversion and low neuroticism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets dive into the genetics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The long (L) allele of the 5-HTTLPR promotor region varies strongly by ethnicity:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Euro/Caucasian:
 58% to 67% have it;
 and 30% to 35% have the double–long (L/L) genotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Asians:
 20% to 30%,
 and only 7% to 10% have L/L
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Latino:
 intermediate,
 with 19% carrying L/L
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
5-HTTLPR is a volume knob for production of serotonin transporters.
 More transporters allow efficient recycling of serotonin in the synapses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The short (S) allele:
 while associated with risk of anxiety and depression under stress,
 recent theories suggest it makes the brain more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plastic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or sensitive to *all* environmental stimuli,
 so that that S–carriers might be happier than L–carriers when placed in an extremely supportive environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are other genes,
 e.g.
 MAOA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
OK.
 So there's an unresolved tension here.
 On the one hand,
 I have a Heideggerian Dasein.
 On the other hand,
 I have these mechanistic set–points determined by genetics,
 neurotransmitter transporters,
 neural wiring.
 The embodied Dasien is some sort of mechanistic outcome of neural architecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I was going to write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

this is not limited to humans
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 but his is more subtle.
 Animals placed under extreme stress also develop depressive symptoms.
 Elephants waste away after the death of a loved one.
 Chimps refuse to eat after the death of the mother.
 The point here is that there is also a backwards–causal effect:
 it is not just our mood is determined by neurotransmitters,
 and our mood is a robotic marionette of those levels,
 but also the inverse:
 tragic events alter the balance,
 and that altered balance has physical side–effects,
 e.g.
 loss of appetite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(I stepped outside,
 and the birds,
 žvirbliai,
 are having a ball.
 Diving and lifting and ...
 surfing.
 There's no English analog to the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

žvirbliai
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 these are small birds.
 Mostly jays,
 I guess.
 Starlings.
 Well,
 except these are *not* starlings.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I used the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surfing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and am reminded of the Stacy Peralta film 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Riding Giants
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This is about a purely joyous activity.
 That particular combination of sun and water on the skin,
 the physical effort,
 the mental concentration to catch the wave,
 the maintenance of balance while also having the freedom of pure movement within that envelope of balance,
 where one can choose to dance as one wishes on the surfboard – Something about this very specific combination is very highly rewarding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What,
 exactly?
 Science does not know or understand the specific mechanisms of joy evoked by surfing.
 Is it seratonin?
 Dopamine?
 How does it compare to heroin?
 MDMA?
 Could you cure depressives by teaching them how to surf?
 (Lets ignore the lack of economic activity:
 it costs money for food.
 Well,
 tropical birds with grandiose plumage are able to expend such energetic outlays because food is abundant.
 But wait,
 are tropical birds more happy than others?
 All that plumage is for mating rituals,
 some of which are complex.
 Do tropical birds get neurotic about mating?
 I'm horny as a toad.
 I really,
 really,
 really need to get laid.
 And the current chances of that happening are approximately nil.
 Much much worse.
 I might never–ever get laid again.
 I've got multiple decades of celibacy behind me,
 and multiple decades of celibacy in front of me,
 and I'm ultra–mega–horny,
 and OMG what does one have to do to get some sex around here?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I mean,
 science,
 that ever–present bystander,
 could give me statistics about what fraction of tropical birds fail to mate.
 Or point out that some huge percentage of them die before adulthood.
 There are children starving in Africa,
 and Ukrainians dying in the war.
 What right have I to complain?
 I'm lucky so far:
 born smart,
 even temperment,
 mostly,
 except for my current ongoing bout of shock (and other misc episodes of my youth,
 someday I should recount these).
 But I was lucky:
 I had oodles and gobs of sex between ages of 17 and 30.
 The very long dry spell is recent,
 and I don't know how to get out of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One obvious technical,
 mechanical solution is to make use of some dating app.
 I am negatively predisposed to this.
 I expect it to be filled with the great mediocrity.
  
\end_layout

